{"id":"2305.06443","submitter":"Bnaya Gross","authors":"Shengling Gao, Leyang Xue, Bnaya Gross, Zhikun She, Daqing Li, Shlomo\n  Havlin","title":"Does k-core percolation belong to the same universality class as\n  interdependent networks?","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  $k$-core percolation and interdependent network (IN) have been extensively\nstudied in their respective fields, but very little is known about similarities\nbetween these two models, in particular with respect to their critical phase\ntransition. In this paper, we explore the critical transition behavior of\nk-core percolation in random networks. Using the node occupancy rate $p$ as the\ncontrol variable and the $k$-core giant component size as the order parameter,\nwe study the critical exponents of the fluctuations of the critical $p$, $p_c$,\nand the order parameter; as well as the critical exponents of the duration of\nthe plateau breakdown and their scaling behavior. We observe that the\nfractality of fluctuations of the giant component found in IN also exists in\nk-core percolation, and can be manifested by a fractal fluctuation dimension,\n$d_f = 3/4$, within a correlation length $\\xi'$ that scales as $\\xi' \\propto\n(p-p_c)^{-\\nu'}$, with $\\nu' = 2$. We note also that same as in IN, the scaling\nbehavior of plateau in k-core also scales at $p_c$, as $\\left\\langle\n\\tau\\right\\rangle \\propto N^{\\psi}$ and near $p_c$, as $\\left\\langle\n\\tau\\right\\rangle \\propto(p-p_c)^{-\\phi}$, where $\\psi=1/3$ and $\\phi=1/2$.\nThese four quantities found here for $k$-core percolation exhibit identical\nscaling behaviors as found for IN with the same critical exponents. These\nresults highly suggest that both systems belong to the same universality class.\nIn addition, analytical arguments for a universal hyper-scaling relation for\nthe fractal fluctuation dimension of the $k$-core giant component and for IN as\nwell as for any mixed-order transition is established. Our investigation\nenhances the comprehension of k-core percolation and supports the\ngeneralization of fractal fluctuations in mixed-order phase transitions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 10 May 2023 20:26:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-12"}
