{"id":"2305.06871","submitter":"Roman Kozlov","authors":"Roman Kozlov","title":"Conservation laws of mean field games equations","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math-ph math.MP math.OC","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Mean field games equations are examined for conservation laws. The system of\nmean field games equations consists of two partial differential equations: the\nHamilton-Jacobi-Bellman equation for the value function and the forward\nKolmogorov equation for the probability density. For separable Hamiltonians,\nthis system has a variational structure, i.e., the equations of the system are\nEuler-Lagrange equations for some Lagrangian functions. Therefore, one can use\nthe Noether theorem to derive the conservation laws using variational and\ndivergence symmetries. In order to find such symmetries, we find symmetries of\nthe PDE system and select variational and divergence ones. The paper considers\nseparable, state-independent Hamiltonians in one-dimensional state space. It\nexamines the most general form of the mean field games system for symmetries\nand conservation laws and identifies particular cases of the system which lead\nto additional symmetries and conservation laws.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 11 May 2023 15:15:23 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-12"}
